1
00:00:18,191 --> 00:00:22,361
Welcome to a night

2
00:00:22,363 --> 00:00:25,231
of total terror.

3
00:00:29,036 --> 00:00:33,606
In 1967, a 27 year old
college drop out from the Bronx

4
00:00:33,608 --> 00:00:38,978
named George A. Romero directed
a low budget horror film.

5
00:00:38,980 --> 00:00:43,749
Night of the Living Dead!

6
00:00:43,751 --> 00:00:47,119
The film introduced the world
to a new kind of monster...

7
00:00:47,121 --> 00:00:49,455
Persons who have recently died

8
00:00:49,457 --> 00:00:55,161
have been returning to life
and committing acts of murder.

9
00:00:55,163 --> 00:00:57,129
...the flesh eating zombie.

10
00:01:01,268 --> 00:01:07,139
This spawned an entire genre
of TV shows and movies, novels,

11
00:01:07,141 --> 00:01:13,245
comic books, video games
and zombie conventions,

12
00:01:13,247 --> 00:01:15,848
thriving industries
to this day.

13
00:01:19,786 --> 00:01:22,121
But at the time "Night of
the Living Dead" was made,

14
00:01:22,123 --> 00:01:23,756
I don't think
audiences were ready

15
00:01:23,758 --> 00:01:25,224
for "Night of the Living Dead."

16
00:01:25,226 --> 00:01:28,160
It spoke to its audience
in ways few horror films

17
00:01:28,162 --> 00:01:29,895
had ever done before.

18
00:01:29,897 --> 00:01:32,298
And I think that's why
they were drawn to it.

19
00:01:32,300 --> 00:01:34,400
The first time you
saw it you realized

20
00:01:34,402 --> 00:01:38,838
it was making a place for itself
in a time capsule of some sort.

21
00:01:38,840 --> 00:01:42,608
No movie had that kind
of impact at that time.

22
00:01:42,610 --> 00:01:45,377
It was this tiny
little movie in Pittsburgh

23
00:01:45,379 --> 00:01:47,146
that seemed to have no chance.

24
00:01:47,148 --> 00:01:49,148
And it, you know,
changed the world.

25
00:01:52,986 --> 00:01:54,286
It was no big thing, man.

26
00:01:54,288 --> 00:01:56,555
Who knew that we were ever even
going to finish this movie.

27
00:01:56,557 --> 00:01:58,324
It was just like a bunch
of people getting together

28
00:01:58,326 --> 00:02:01,093
and we were going
to try to make a movie.

29
00:02:01,095 --> 00:02:05,431
And none of us knew that it
was ever going to get finished.

30
00:02:05,433 --> 00:02:08,767
Let alone become something
as well-known as it is.

31
00:02:13,573 --> 00:02:16,308
George Romero started his first
film production company

32
00:02:16,310 --> 00:02:19,545
in the city of Pittsburgh
in 1963.

33
00:02:19,547 --> 00:02:21,614
He called it, the Latent Image.

34
00:02:21,616 --> 00:02:24,383
♪ It's a beautiful day
in this neighborhood ♪

35
00:02:24,385 --> 00:02:26,552
♪ A beautiful day
for a neighbor ♪

36
00:02:26,554 --> 00:02:28,721
♪ Would you be mine

37
00:02:28,723 --> 00:02:30,322
♪ Could you be mine

38
00:02:30,324 --> 00:02:32,358
We all weaned into the business

39
00:02:32,360 --> 00:02:35,461
on Fred Rogers,
"Mr. Rogers Neighborhood."

40
00:02:35,463 --> 00:02:39,632
Almost everybody in Pittsburgh
who works in the biz now

41
00:02:39,634 --> 00:02:41,467
worked for Fred for a while.

42
00:02:41,469 --> 00:02:47,206
♪ I have always wanted to have
a neighbor just like you ♪

43
00:02:47,208 --> 00:02:49,909
Romero and his partners
make several short films

44
00:02:49,911 --> 00:02:52,111
for the children's
television series,

45
00:02:52,113 --> 00:02:55,114
including
"Things that Feel Soft"

46
00:02:55,116 --> 00:02:58,584
and "Mr. Rogers
Gets a Tonsillectomy."

47
00:02:58,586 --> 00:03:04,924
Up in the ceiling were
some lights I could see.

48
00:03:04,926 --> 00:03:09,695
And the kind eyes

49
00:03:09,697 --> 00:03:12,131
of the people
in the operating room.

50
00:03:12,133 --> 00:03:16,769
Even though they wore masks,
I could see their kind eyes.

51
00:03:16,771 --> 00:03:19,638
Which remains one of the
scariest movies I've ever done.

52
00:03:22,309 --> 00:03:27,146
The Latent Image also finds
opportunity in a new industry.

53
00:03:27,148 --> 00:03:30,082
At the time, you know,
commercials were live.

54
00:03:30,084 --> 00:03:32,718
The beer commercials used
to be the sportscaster.

55
00:03:32,720 --> 00:03:34,687
Even when you were
able to drink.

56
00:03:34,689 --> 00:03:38,424
You were actually able to drink
beer on camera in a commercial.

57
00:03:38,426 --> 00:03:40,259
These guys, by the time,

58
00:03:40,261 --> 00:03:44,363
if you went into extra innings,

59
00:03:44,365 --> 00:03:48,834
it was like...

60
00:03:48,836 --> 00:03:50,336
And all of a sudden,
we come along and say,

61
00:03:50,338 --> 00:03:52,338
"You know, you can do
this shit on film, man."

62
00:03:52,340 --> 00:03:53,973
When you hit a dry spell,

63
00:03:53,975 --> 00:03:55,908
what's the natural way
to wet it down?

64
00:03:55,910 --> 00:03:57,309
Hey honey! How about a beer?

65
00:03:57,311 --> 00:03:58,844
With a tall, cold Duke.

66
00:03:58,846 --> 00:04:03,115
Duquesne beer at the time,
which is no longer.

67
00:04:03,117 --> 00:04:06,619
Great times, great beer,
they go together.

68
00:04:06,621 --> 00:04:09,755
And there's no better beer
for great times than Iron City.

69
00:04:09,757 --> 00:04:11,323
Iron's still there.

70
00:04:11,325 --> 00:04:12,992
Iron! Gimme an Iron!

71
00:04:12,994 --> 00:04:15,160
And how about that
Iron City flavor?

72
00:04:15,162 --> 00:04:16,829
Rich. Robust.

73
00:04:16,831 --> 00:04:18,063
Delicious.

74
00:04:18,065 --> 00:04:21,333
I could shoot, I could record,
I was an editor.

75
00:04:21,335 --> 00:04:23,469
You know, I wound
up doing it all.

76
00:04:23,471 --> 00:04:24,937
So it was all learn by doing.

77
00:04:24,939 --> 00:04:27,606
I shot more film
at the Latent Image

78
00:04:27,608 --> 00:04:30,009
than I've shot over the course

79
00:04:30,011 --> 00:04:33,279
of all the feature films
that I've made.

80
00:04:33,281 --> 00:04:35,347
I mean, because we were
shooting all the time.

81
00:04:35,349 --> 00:04:37,082
In those days, it was all film.

82
00:04:37,084 --> 00:04:39,385
So, you had to wait for it
to come back from the lab.

83
00:04:39,387 --> 00:04:40,686
There were local labs.

84
00:04:40,688 --> 00:04:42,254
They were not that reliable.

85
00:04:42,256 --> 00:04:44,623
You'd put your heart
into shooting this stuff

86
00:04:44,625 --> 00:04:45,858
and the guy would
call up and say,

87
00:04:45,860 --> 00:04:48,861
"You know what,
we fucked it up."

88
00:04:56,536 --> 00:04:59,938
But once the film came back,
as long as it looked okay man,

89
00:04:59,940 --> 00:05:01,674
as soon as the film
walked in the door

90
00:05:01,676 --> 00:05:03,976
I'd sit there
until it was edited.

91
00:05:03,978 --> 00:05:08,781
I'd sit there sometimes
36, 48 hours, get it done.

92
00:05:08,783 --> 00:05:10,249
You know I basically
lived there.

93
00:05:10,251 --> 00:05:13,952
And I just lived, breathed
and drank the stuff.

94
00:05:13,954 --> 00:05:15,888
No thought
for family or whatever;

95
00:05:15,890 --> 00:05:19,024
I just was, making movies, man.

96
00:05:19,026 --> 00:05:22,661
Preview films presents,
"The Calgon Story."

97
00:05:22,663 --> 00:05:24,430
We did this thing called,
"The Calgon Story."

98
00:05:24,432 --> 00:05:27,232
It was a knock off
of, "Fantastic Voyage."

99
00:05:27,234 --> 00:05:28,734
Add the Calgon!

100
00:05:28,736 --> 00:05:31,804
And it was the biggest
commercial that we've ever done.

101
00:05:31,806 --> 00:05:32,938
It's working!

102
00:05:32,940 --> 00:05:34,673
The grey is gone!

103
00:05:34,675 --> 00:05:36,175
The fibers are clean!

104
00:05:36,177 --> 00:05:37,810
Let's get out of here.

105
00:05:37,812 --> 00:05:39,078
I think I'm in love with you.

106
00:05:39,080 --> 00:05:43,182
And they wanted 35
so we sacrificed our profit

107
00:05:43,184 --> 00:05:46,885
and went out
and bought a 35mm camera.

108
00:05:46,887 --> 00:05:49,188
We started to think
that we could actually

109
00:05:49,190 --> 00:05:50,789
make movies, you know.

110
00:05:50,791 --> 00:05:52,858
When we finally
had the equipment

111
00:05:52,860 --> 00:05:55,027
and we thought we could
make a movie, I wanted,

112
00:05:55,029 --> 00:06:00,299
I had this really high minded
idea to this Bergmanesque

113
00:06:00,301 --> 00:06:05,104
sort of "Virgin Spring"
kind of a movie.

114
00:06:05,106 --> 00:06:08,073
And so I wrote this thing
about two teenagers

115
00:06:08,075 --> 00:06:09,608
in the middle ages.

116
00:06:09,610 --> 00:06:12,778
I mean, boy, talk about reaching
for the moon, right?

117
00:06:12,780 --> 00:06:15,180
Romero's search
for investors for his first

118
00:06:15,182 --> 00:06:18,417
feature-length screenplay,
"Whine of the Fawn,"

119
00:06:18,419 --> 00:06:20,419
ultimately failed.

120
00:06:20,421 --> 00:06:23,322
Eventually we abandoned
it and decided to do,

121
00:06:23,324 --> 00:06:26,325
maybe we should do something
a little more commercial.

122
00:06:26,327 --> 00:06:30,129
And, so we decided
to do a horror flick.

123
00:06:30,131 --> 00:06:33,365
And I had read a novel
called, "I am Legend."

124
00:06:33,367 --> 00:06:35,100
A Richard Matheson novel.

125
00:06:35,102 --> 00:06:38,504
And it seemed to me that it
was about revolution underneath.

126
00:06:47,180 --> 00:06:51,784
But we were also
very aware of the time,

127
00:06:51,786 --> 00:06:55,154
you know, and the sort
of anger of the 60s.

128
00:06:55,156 --> 00:06:57,756
The year was 1967.

129
00:07:03,730 --> 00:07:06,465
The U.S. was fighting
an increasingly unpopular war

130
00:07:06,467 --> 00:07:08,066
in Vietnam.

131
00:07:17,076 --> 00:07:20,078
At home in the U.S.,
despite historic strides made

132
00:07:20,080 --> 00:07:24,249
during the civil rights era,
rampant racism still ruled.

133
00:07:26,186 --> 00:07:29,588
After suffering continued
unchecked discrimination,

134
00:07:29,590 --> 00:07:33,559
African Americans
took to the streets.

135
00:07:33,561 --> 00:07:36,662
Some called it rioting.

136
00:07:36,664 --> 00:07:40,065
Others called it revolution.

137
00:07:40,067 --> 00:07:43,969
We stand on the eve
of a black revolution, brothers.

138
00:07:43,971 --> 00:07:46,472
Masses of our people
are in the streets.

139
00:07:46,474 --> 00:07:48,307
They're fighting tit for tat,

140
00:07:48,309 --> 00:07:49,808
two for two,

141
00:07:49,810 --> 00:07:53,278
an eye for an eye
and a life for a life.

142
00:07:53,280 --> 00:07:56,815
The summer of '67 was the summer
of riots in Newark and Detroit.

143
00:07:56,817 --> 00:08:01,153
And the idea of
the "American Ghetto"

144
00:08:01,155 --> 00:08:04,957
really started to take hold
in the public consciousness

145
00:08:04,959 --> 00:08:08,060
as a kind of symptom
of the Civil Rights movement

146
00:08:08,062 --> 00:08:10,362
whereas in the 50s
and early 60s

147
00:08:10,364 --> 00:08:12,197
it would have been
lunch counters

148
00:08:12,199 --> 00:08:14,533
and marches in southern
cities and busses.

149
00:08:14,535 --> 00:08:16,168
Now, it was about anger.

150
00:08:16,170 --> 00:08:19,238
There was a good deal
of sort of anger.

151
00:08:19,240 --> 00:08:22,508
You know, I think mostly
that the 60s didn't work.

152
00:08:22,510 --> 00:08:24,276
You know, we thought
we had changed the world

153
00:08:24,278 --> 00:08:27,446
or were part of some
sort of a reform

154
00:08:27,448 --> 00:08:32,017
that was going to make
things better.

155
00:08:32,019 --> 00:08:33,552
And all of a sudden
it wasn't any better.

156
00:08:33,554 --> 00:08:34,820
It wasn't any different.

157
00:08:34,822 --> 00:08:37,389
Let's get off the street!

158
00:08:37,391 --> 00:08:39,825
Get the lead out of your ass!

159
00:08:39,827 --> 00:08:43,829
So I think there was a bit of
rage, a bit of disappointment.

160
00:08:46,366 --> 00:08:49,134
So I invented these characters.

161
00:08:49,136 --> 00:08:50,969
In my mind
they were just ghouls.

162
00:08:50,971 --> 00:08:52,237
The dead are
coming back to life.

163
00:08:52,239 --> 00:08:53,639
That's the revolution.

164
00:08:53,641 --> 00:08:55,941
That's the big thing
that everybody's missing.

165
00:08:55,943 --> 00:08:58,510
And we just wanted to make
as ballsy a horror film

166
00:08:58,512 --> 00:09:00,078
as we could make.

167
00:09:00,080 --> 00:09:02,114
Romero and nine
other investors --

168
00:09:02,116 --> 00:09:04,850
including several partners
from the Latent Image --

169
00:09:04,852 --> 00:09:07,953
form a new company
called, "Image 10."

170
00:09:07,955 --> 00:09:11,857
They rent an abandoned farmhouse
for the film's primary location.

171
00:09:11,859 --> 00:09:14,459
Initially, ten of us
kicked in 600 bucks,

172
00:09:14,461 --> 00:09:15,961
it was enough
to rent the farmhouse,

173
00:09:15,963 --> 00:09:18,830
buy some film stock,
and we started to shoot.

174
00:09:18,832 --> 00:09:20,032
We started to shoot not knowing

175
00:09:20,034 --> 00:09:21,914
if we were ever
going to finish.

176
00:09:25,271 --> 00:09:28,040
Romero is 27 years old.

177
00:09:54,133 --> 00:09:56,168
We lived on that farmhouse.

178
00:09:56,170 --> 00:09:59,471
And we had to go out
to the little stream

179
00:09:59,473 --> 00:10:02,307
in order to wash off.

180
00:10:02,309 --> 00:10:04,343
So it was real
guerilla stuff, you know.

181
00:10:04,345 --> 00:10:05,978
Talk about dedication.

182
00:10:05,980 --> 00:10:07,879
And everybody went
along with this!

183
00:10:07,881 --> 00:10:09,715
You know, somehow I'd
say, "Okay, guys."

184
00:10:09,717 --> 00:10:12,684
It's going to be rough, but,
you know, we'll make a movie."

185
00:10:12,686 --> 00:10:15,988
And everybody'd say,
"All right."

186
00:10:15,990 --> 00:10:17,422
Did that surprise you?

187
00:10:17,424 --> 00:10:19,491
It did! It did!
Completely.

188
00:10:19,493 --> 00:10:22,060
I'd expect people to say,
"What are you, crazy?"

189
00:10:22,062 --> 00:10:25,263
George Romero's jobs
include cinematographer,

190
00:10:25,265 --> 00:10:27,199
editor, and director.

191
00:10:27,201 --> 00:10:29,267
I didn't know very much then.

192
00:10:29,269 --> 00:10:30,902
What's a director
s'posed to do?

193
00:10:30,904 --> 00:10:32,938
I dunno!

194
00:10:32,940 --> 00:10:34,039
Walk over here!

195
00:10:34,041 --> 00:10:36,308
I think the first time
you try to do anything,

196
00:10:36,310 --> 00:10:40,212
especially when you're trying
to do something new, um,

197
00:10:40,214 --> 00:10:42,581
you're learning on the job.

198
00:10:42,583 --> 00:10:46,551
And essentially everything
that can go wrong will go wrong.

199
00:10:46,553 --> 00:10:50,055
Whether it's issues
with cameras or cast members

200
00:10:50,057 --> 00:10:52,824
who really don't have
a lot of experience.

201
00:10:52,826 --> 00:10:56,294
Crew members who don't quite
know what they're doing.

202
00:10:56,296 --> 00:10:57,829
I tried to build a clay hand

203
00:10:57,831 --> 00:11:01,867
and I tried to leave it hollow
and fill it with blood.

204
00:11:06,072 --> 00:11:07,439
It looks like shit!

205
00:11:07,441 --> 00:11:10,275
I mean, it's, it's not great.

206
00:11:10,277 --> 00:11:13,812
There were very few independents
being done at that point.

207
00:11:13,814 --> 00:11:17,215
And here's a guy
from Pittsburgh, PA,

208
00:11:17,217 --> 00:11:19,017
who gets an idea for a film,

209
00:11:19,019 --> 00:11:21,920
manages to raise
a small amount of money

210
00:11:21,922 --> 00:11:23,955
and just had
the courage, the passion,

211
00:11:23,957 --> 00:11:26,725
the persistence to get it done.

212
00:11:26,727 --> 00:11:28,994
It's really remarkable a film

213
00:11:28,996 --> 00:11:32,564
that has become such a classic
came out of an environment

214
00:11:32,566 --> 00:11:37,302
where everyone was
learning on the job.

215
00:11:37,304 --> 00:11:40,005
Many in the cast and crew
take on multiple jobs

216
00:11:40,007 --> 00:11:42,407
to make up for
the lack in budget.

217
00:11:44,143 --> 00:11:47,713
Russ Streiner's duties
include producer and actor.

218
00:11:47,715 --> 00:11:51,016
John Russo's include
co-screenwriter and zombie.

219
00:11:51,018 --> 00:11:53,785
Initially I had written
it as a short story.

220
00:11:53,787 --> 00:11:57,189
And then I started to adapt
it into a screenplay.

221
00:11:57,191 --> 00:11:59,858
And then we actually started
to have to start to shoot,

222
00:11:59,860 --> 00:12:03,228
so Jack Russo took over
finishing the screenplay

223
00:12:03,230 --> 00:12:07,165
and we collaborated
on it after that point.

224
00:12:07,167 --> 00:12:11,436
Karl Hardman is producer,
make-up artist and actor.

225
00:12:11,438 --> 00:12:14,239
Marilyn Eastman is
make-up artist and actor.

226
00:12:14,241 --> 00:12:17,075
Karl and Marilyn started
this audio production company.

227
00:12:17,077 --> 00:12:20,679
And so they provided all
the audio recording equipment

228
00:12:20,681 --> 00:12:22,714
when we made
"Night of the Living Dead."

229
00:12:22,716 --> 00:12:26,685
They did the zombie make ups
and were incredibly energetic

230
00:12:26,687 --> 00:12:30,388
and just would do any job
that needed to be done.

231
00:12:30,390 --> 00:12:34,659
It was a new impetus
for people to uh,

232
00:12:34,661 --> 00:12:37,462
honestly, to fuck
the system, you know?

233
00:12:37,464 --> 00:12:38,964
It's like we can
do this ourselves.

234
00:12:38,966 --> 00:12:40,365
We don't have
to go to Hollywood

235
00:12:40,367 --> 00:12:42,100
with our little script
about zombies

236
00:12:42,102 --> 00:12:44,736
that everybody would
never have supported.

237
00:12:44,738 --> 00:12:46,271
It's too freaky, uh,

238
00:12:46,273 --> 00:12:48,607
they're too busy making
Charlton Heston epics,

239
00:12:48,609 --> 00:12:51,710
you know,
and uh "Mary Poppins."

240
00:12:51,712 --> 00:12:54,045
Friends, friends of friends
and colleagues

241
00:12:54,047 --> 00:12:55,814
comprise the rest of the crew.

242
00:12:55,816 --> 00:13:00,519
"Night of the Living Dead" was
very much a collaborative work.

243
00:13:00,521 --> 00:13:02,487
There was a sense
of improvisation on the set,

244
00:13:02,489 --> 00:13:05,390
which I think helps the movie.

245
00:13:05,392 --> 00:13:07,692
Crews, you know,
it's where it's at, man.

246
00:13:07,694 --> 00:13:11,830
I mean, you're reliant
on all these people.

247
00:13:11,832 --> 00:13:14,800
And it's the only way
it happens, ever.

248
00:13:14,802 --> 00:13:16,535
You don't make the movie,
you don't make the movie,

249
00:13:16,537 --> 00:13:19,171
you can't go out
and make a movie!

250
00:13:19,173 --> 00:13:22,941
You know, you can't make
this movie without this guy!

251
00:13:22,943 --> 00:13:26,478
And look, he's doing it all!

252
00:13:26,480 --> 00:13:29,514
Look, isn't it,
that's what it is, man!

253
00:13:29,516 --> 00:13:30,749
Alright, Vince,
hit him in the head,

254
00:13:30,751 --> 00:13:32,651
right between the eyes.

255
00:13:32,653 --> 00:13:34,319
For many, like investor,

256
00:13:34,321 --> 00:13:37,522
production director
and actor Vince Survinski,

257
00:13:37,524 --> 00:13:40,292
this is their first experience
with filmmaking.

258
00:13:40,294 --> 00:13:43,228
Vince Survinski owned
a roller rink in Pittsburgh

259
00:13:43,230 --> 00:13:46,264
and said, "Ah, I always
wanted to get into movies."

260
00:13:46,266 --> 00:13:48,500
Vince was always
a go-to guy.

261
00:13:48,502 --> 00:13:49,968
He would get things done.

262
00:13:49,970 --> 00:13:51,436
We'd all be sitting
around puzzling,

263
00:13:51,438 --> 00:13:53,438
"Oh, this is a great farm house,
but you have to wade

264
00:13:53,440 --> 00:13:56,341
across a stream
to get over there."

265
00:13:56,343 --> 00:13:58,577
So Vince'd say, "Ah, I'll
build a little bridge."

266
00:13:58,579 --> 00:14:00,545
And Goddammit,
with his own hands

267
00:14:00,547 --> 00:14:02,080
he built this
little wooden bridge

268
00:14:02,082 --> 00:14:04,002
that you could actually
drive a car over.

269
00:14:07,753 --> 00:14:10,288
Oh, the demolition crew!

270
00:14:10,290 --> 00:14:14,659
Vince's brother, Reg, and he had
a partner named Tony Pantonello.

271
00:14:14,661 --> 00:14:16,094
They used to do fireworks.

272
00:14:16,096 --> 00:14:18,530
They were not the Zambelli's
but, you know,

273
00:14:18,532 --> 00:14:20,599
if you needed some fireworks
down at your church

274
00:14:20,601 --> 00:14:22,267
you called these guys.

275
00:14:22,269 --> 00:14:24,569
They did all
the pyrotechnical stuff

276
00:14:24,571 --> 00:14:26,771
and they were hilarious guys,
I mean, you know.

277
00:14:26,773 --> 00:14:29,941
Tony would have this cigar
constantly burning in his mouth

278
00:14:29,943 --> 00:14:31,910
and he's working
putting a fuse together

279
00:14:31,912 --> 00:14:33,912
and he couldn't see very well,
so he's like this

280
00:14:33,914 --> 00:14:35,747
and this cigar and I'm like,

281
00:14:35,749 --> 00:14:38,383
"Tony, you're gonna
blow your fingers off!"

282
00:14:38,385 --> 00:14:39,918
They did all the squibs.

283
00:14:39,920 --> 00:14:42,487
Squibwork and the explosives,
and all that.

284
00:14:45,458 --> 00:14:48,460
Actor, lighting person,
and investor Bill Hinzman

285
00:14:48,462 --> 00:14:52,898
and John Russo both volunteer
to be set on fire.

286
00:14:52,900 --> 00:14:55,367
Given no protective clothing
they simply agree

287
00:14:55,369 --> 00:14:58,403
to roll on the grass
if they get hot.

288
00:14:58,405 --> 00:15:01,206
I think maybe that
was Reg's suggestion.

289
00:15:01,208 --> 00:15:04,576
"It starts to feel hot,
just lie down."

290
00:15:04,578 --> 00:15:06,778
"Want anything from
the supply wagon, Kuss?"

291
00:15:06,780 --> 00:15:09,281
No, we're alright.

292
00:15:09,283 --> 00:15:11,549
Hey, Kass, put that thing
all the way into the fire,

293
00:15:11,551 --> 00:15:14,085
we don't want it
getting up again!

294
00:15:14,087 --> 00:15:16,288
Chief, Chief McClelland,
how's everything going?

295
00:15:16,290 --> 00:15:19,925
Aw, things aren't going too bad,
men are taking it pretty good.

296
00:15:19,927 --> 00:15:22,327
You want to get on the other
side of the road over there!

297
00:15:22,329 --> 00:15:25,830
Bill Cardille who was
a TV personality,

298
00:15:25,832 --> 00:15:28,633
he came out to be the news guy.

299
00:15:28,635 --> 00:15:32,437
And he had to interview
Kuss as the Sheriff.

300
00:15:32,439 --> 00:15:34,773
So, all those lines,
the greatest lines in the movie

301
00:15:34,775 --> 00:15:36,641
were all ad libbed by Kuss.

302
00:15:36,643 --> 00:15:38,343
Are they slow moving, Chief?

303
00:15:38,345 --> 00:15:41,913
Yeah, they're dead,
they're all messed up.

304
00:15:46,519 --> 00:15:48,853
All that shit was
completely off the cuff.

305
00:15:48,855 --> 00:15:53,091
This is Bill Cardille,
WIIC, TV 11 news.

306
00:15:53,093 --> 00:15:56,728
Bill Cardille, almost every
Saturday night he would plug us

307
00:15:56,730 --> 00:15:58,363
and say there are these
guys in Pittsburgh

308
00:15:58,365 --> 00:16:00,365
that are actually
making a horror movie.

309
00:16:00,367 --> 00:16:02,568
And I'm going to go out
and I'm going to appear in it.

310
00:16:02,569 --> 00:16:04,803
So we got a little
bit of a profile.

311
00:16:04,805 --> 00:16:07,806
And, because of that profile
I think people believed

312
00:16:07,808 --> 00:16:11,276
that we were going to,
probably more than us,

313
00:16:11,278 --> 00:16:13,611
that we were actually
going to finish this movie.

314
00:16:13,613 --> 00:16:15,013
Yeah, Chief, we're going
to stay with it

315
00:16:15,015 --> 00:16:16,748
until we meet up
with the National Guard.

316
00:16:16,750 --> 00:16:18,483
- Where'd you get the coffee?
- One of the volunteers.

317
00:16:18,485 --> 00:16:19,851
You're doing all the work,
why don't you take it.

318
00:16:19,853 --> 00:16:22,220
Bill Cardille came out
and brought the camera guy

319
00:16:22,222 --> 00:16:26,024
from Channel 11
and he brought his gear.

320
00:16:26,026 --> 00:16:29,728
The helicopter pilot
for local radio station KQV

321
00:16:29,730 --> 00:16:32,964
lets Russ Streiner ride
with him to get aerial shots.

322
00:16:36,068 --> 00:16:38,236
We called the Police,
we got real police

323
00:16:38,238 --> 00:16:39,971
to come out and cooperate.

324
00:16:39,973 --> 00:16:43,141
I mean, all we had to do
was call up and say, "Guys!"

325
00:16:43,143 --> 00:16:44,676
And, you know and they
brought the vans out

326
00:16:44,678 --> 00:16:46,378
and the dogs
and everything else!

327
00:16:46,380 --> 00:16:48,646
You know, it was amazing
all the cooperation

328
00:16:48,648 --> 00:16:49,881
that we used to get.

329
00:16:49,883 --> 00:16:50,949
I mean, it was incredible.

330
00:16:50,951 --> 00:16:53,385
Everybody was sort of with us

331
00:16:53,387 --> 00:16:56,921
because we were trying
to actually make a movie.

332
00:16:56,923 --> 00:16:59,457
The dozens of zombies
are played by friends,

333
00:16:59,459 --> 00:17:03,261
family, local townfolk
and clients of Romero's

334
00:17:03,263 --> 00:17:06,998
commercial production company,
the Latent Image.

335
00:17:07,000 --> 00:17:10,635
Most of the zombies were people
we used to work with.

336
00:17:10,637 --> 00:17:12,470
People that, that
were giving us jobs.

337
00:17:12,472 --> 00:17:15,473
Advertising people,
a couple of news guys.

338
00:17:18,711 --> 00:17:21,646
A lot of the zombies
were clients of ours

339
00:17:21,648 --> 00:17:23,748
from ad agencies.

340
00:17:23,750 --> 00:17:27,052
Humoring us,
saying, "Sure, okay.

341
00:17:27,054 --> 00:17:28,086
I'll come out."

342
00:17:29,855 --> 00:17:34,392
A woman came out and was willing
to appear nude from behind.

343
00:17:34,394 --> 00:17:37,095
I don't know if there's any
such thing as a bad zombie.

344
00:17:37,097 --> 00:17:39,064
I mean, I love them all.

345
00:17:39,066 --> 00:17:41,166
But, you know, you get
people who come out.

346
00:17:41,168 --> 00:17:43,802
I mean, if I do anything,
if I make a gesture,

347
00:17:43,804 --> 00:17:45,537
if I'm talking
to twenty zombies

348
00:17:45,539 --> 00:17:47,772
and they're all looking at me
saying, "Well, what do I do?"

349
00:17:47,774 --> 00:17:49,007
"Well, you walk
over here."

350
00:17:49,009 --> 00:17:52,444
And if I go like that,
everybody does that.

351
00:17:52,446 --> 00:17:55,113
So, pretty much just say,
"Do whatever you want.

352
00:17:55,115 --> 00:17:56,714
Do your best zombie, man."

353
00:17:56,716 --> 00:18:00,251
And you get some
incredibly creative things.

354
00:18:02,154 --> 00:18:03,988
One of the investors

355
00:18:03,990 --> 00:18:06,491
Ross Harris was a meat packer.

356
00:18:06,493 --> 00:18:09,127
So he brought
all these entrails,

357
00:18:09,129 --> 00:18:10,730
so it was pretty rough.

358
00:18:12,865 --> 00:18:15,066
That was all real stuff,
real intestines,

359
00:18:15,068 --> 00:18:17,735
real livers, cow livers.

360
00:18:21,974 --> 00:18:23,508
We wanted to push the envelope,

361
00:18:23,510 --> 00:18:26,444
let's see what
we can do with this.

362
00:18:26,446 --> 00:18:29,280
Just bring out buckets of stuff
and... I'm telling you, boy,

363
00:18:29,282 --> 00:18:32,016
people that come to be zombies
they're really dedicated.

364
00:18:32,018 --> 00:18:35,286
They'll dig into that
stuff and chew on it

365
00:18:39,992 --> 00:18:41,659
and I'm going, "Oy!"

366
00:18:41,661 --> 00:18:44,195
You'll never get me to do that!

367
00:18:48,234 --> 00:18:50,602
That's guts!

368
00:18:50,604 --> 00:18:52,570
It's guts!

369
00:18:57,309 --> 00:18:59,344
When I was gonna show it,
I'm thinking to myself

370
00:18:59,346 --> 00:19:01,946
they're probably just gonna say,
"That sucked Mr. Chris."

371
00:19:01,948 --> 00:19:03,748
Or whatever it may be.

372
00:19:03,750 --> 00:19:07,352
And sure enough, it was the--
it was the complete opposite.

373
00:19:10,022 --> 00:19:12,490
It's amazing the impact
that this movie made,

374
00:19:12,492 --> 00:19:15,260
that this guy made--
you know, with no budget.

375
00:19:15,262 --> 00:19:17,228
How it still was important

376
00:19:17,230 --> 00:19:19,731
and how it still resonates
with everyone who watches it.

377
00:19:19,733 --> 00:19:22,834
When they were dead, they, um,

378
00:19:22,836 --> 00:19:25,436
they were acting
like with no muscles,

379
00:19:25,438 --> 00:19:27,238
they had like, to stay.

380
00:19:27,240 --> 00:19:28,239
What's the name of that?

381
00:19:28,241 --> 00:19:29,174
What's the name of that?

382
00:19:29,176 --> 00:19:30,341
Starts with "R."

383
00:19:30,343 --> 00:19:32,377
- Riga...
- Who said it?

384
00:19:32,379 --> 00:19:35,346
The whole curriculum I have with
the kids is where they learn

385
00:19:35,348 --> 00:19:37,549
literacy through the process
of making movies.

386
00:19:37,551 --> 00:19:38,550
Rigor mortis.

387
00:19:38,552 --> 00:19:39,817
Say it again.

388
00:19:39,819 --> 00:19:40,952
Rigor mortis.

389
00:19:40,954 --> 00:19:41,920
Say it again.

390
00:19:41,922 --> 00:19:43,054
Rigor mortis.

391
00:19:43,056 --> 00:19:44,889
And what happens with that?

392
00:19:44,891 --> 00:19:48,159
Christopher Cruz teaches his
literacy through film program

393
00:19:48,161 --> 00:19:50,495
in the Bronx, New York.

394
00:19:50,497 --> 00:19:52,363
George Romero
grew up in the Bronx

395
00:19:52,365 --> 00:19:54,933
before moving to Pittsburgh.

396
00:19:54,935 --> 00:19:59,370
And it was the old days
of the Sharks and the Jets.

397
00:19:59,372 --> 00:20:03,408
And people, most people
thought I was Italian

398
00:20:03,410 --> 00:20:07,378
so I got away, I think
I got away with my hide,

399
00:20:07,380 --> 00:20:09,747
the Golden Guineas
left me alone,

400
00:20:09,749 --> 00:20:11,983
until they found
out I was Spanish.

401
00:20:11,985 --> 00:20:14,185
Then I was a Shark, you know.

402
00:20:14,187 --> 00:20:17,255
I was never really
into any of that stuff.

403
00:20:17,257 --> 00:20:19,691
I just wanted to make movies.

404
00:20:26,332 --> 00:20:29,000
This movie to me
what's so gorgeous,

405
00:20:29,002 --> 00:20:31,169
even the way it starts,
just that road,

406
00:20:31,171 --> 00:20:33,571
and there are different ways
to make horror films,

407
00:20:33,573 --> 00:20:35,840
what I enjoy about this
is that right away,

408
00:20:35,842 --> 00:20:37,842
the music is very disturbing

409
00:20:37,844 --> 00:20:42,247
and telegraphs that you're
going to get into something

410
00:20:42,249 --> 00:20:44,983
that's going to be scary.

411
00:20:44,985 --> 00:20:47,418
But then, you know,
they go to a graveyard,

412
00:20:47,420 --> 00:20:50,021
and they have their little
dialogue about the length

413
00:20:50,023 --> 00:20:52,924
of the trip and they got
started late and so on.

414
00:20:52,926 --> 00:20:54,892
They ought to make
the day the time changes

415
00:20:54,894 --> 00:20:56,060
the first day of summer.

416
00:20:56,062 --> 00:20:57,462
What?

417
00:20:57,464 --> 00:20:59,764
Well, it's 8 o'clock
and it's still light.

418
00:20:59,766 --> 00:21:02,467
A lot of good the extra
day light does us.

419
00:21:02,469 --> 00:21:04,469
We've still got
a 3 hour drive back.

420
00:21:04,471 --> 00:21:06,304
We're not going to be home
until after midnight.

421
00:21:06,306 --> 00:21:09,507
So it's mundane you know,
there's a mundanity to it

422
00:21:09,509 --> 00:21:13,444
and that is um, I think
a very modern approach.

423
00:21:13,446 --> 00:21:17,115
It even came following
a bunch of low budget films

424
00:21:17,117 --> 00:21:19,417
that basically, like
white girls in bikinis

425
00:21:19,419 --> 00:21:21,252
being chased by guys
wearing shag carpeting

426
00:21:21,254 --> 00:21:22,894
being kind of monster.

427
00:21:24,423 --> 00:21:27,425
Before "Night," audiences
of horror were accustomed

428
00:21:27,427 --> 00:21:31,229
to space aliens,
radioactive mutations

429
00:21:31,231 --> 00:21:35,133
and traditional
gothic monsters.

430
00:21:35,135 --> 00:21:36,768
And by not doing
that kind of stuff,

431
00:21:36,770 --> 00:21:39,237
by making it just
as real as possible,

432
00:21:39,239 --> 00:21:40,772
it became this
whole other thing.

433
00:21:40,774 --> 00:21:43,041
It's not even
a haunted cemetery,

434
00:21:43,043 --> 00:21:45,476
it looks like a big open place
where they can park their car

435
00:21:45,478 --> 00:21:50,014
and they can go to the grave
and it'll be fine.

436
00:21:50,016 --> 00:21:53,151
It's still spooky, the music
is indicating something to come

437
00:21:53,153 --> 00:21:55,987
but it's essentially
a day in the life episode

438
00:21:55,989 --> 00:21:57,221
of these characters.

439
00:21:57,223 --> 00:22:00,158
Boy, you used to really
be scared here.

440
00:22:00,160 --> 00:22:01,626
Johnny!

441
00:22:01,628 --> 00:22:03,061
You're still afraid!

442
00:22:03,063 --> 00:22:06,197
It's to me one of the first sort
of post-modern horror movies

443
00:22:06,199 --> 00:22:09,334
in that it is
commenting on itself.

444
00:22:09,336 --> 00:22:12,537
They're coming
to get you, Barbara!

445
00:22:12,539 --> 00:22:14,605
That's what's so brilliant
about that famous line,

446
00:22:14,607 --> 00:22:16,407
"They're coming
to get you, Barbara!"

447
00:22:16,409 --> 00:22:20,378
is that he's commenting
on a horror movie.

448
00:22:20,380 --> 00:22:22,513
They're coming for you!

449
00:22:22,515 --> 00:22:24,716
Look, there comes
one of them now!

450
00:22:24,718 --> 00:22:26,484
Now, of course,
years later we have "Scream"

451
00:22:26,486 --> 00:22:28,720
and other films like that,
and they're self-reflexive,

452
00:22:28,722 --> 00:22:31,489
but in this obnoxious
nudge-nudge, wink-wink way,

453
00:22:31,491 --> 00:22:32,857
where it's like the audience,

454
00:22:32,859 --> 00:22:34,258
well we've seen all this before

455
00:22:34,260 --> 00:22:36,027
let's make fun
of the characters.

456
00:22:36,029 --> 00:22:37,862
That's not how it
functions in this movie.

457
00:22:37,864 --> 00:22:40,631
It functions
as two people, you know

458
00:22:40,633 --> 00:22:44,302
the brother is kind of teasing
and scare the sister,

459
00:22:44,304 --> 00:22:47,538
and then when it comes true,

460
00:22:47,540 --> 00:22:50,775
to me this is absolutely
stunningly awesome.

461
00:22:54,246 --> 00:22:55,646
Johnny!

462
00:22:55,648 --> 00:22:57,482
Help me!

463
00:22:57,484 --> 00:22:59,050
The horror just
came out of nowhere.

464
00:22:59,052 --> 00:23:01,719
It just kind of shocked you.

465
00:23:01,721 --> 00:23:03,488
It scared me to death.

466
00:23:03,490 --> 00:23:08,760
It disorients you just right
from the beginning of the movie;

467
00:23:08,762 --> 00:23:12,296
you're being told that places
that shouldn't be very scary

468
00:23:12,298 --> 00:23:14,265
are actually going
to be really scary.

469
00:23:14,267 --> 00:23:16,167
Situations where
you should feel safe,

470
00:23:16,169 --> 00:23:17,668
you're not going to feel safe.

471
00:23:17,670 --> 00:23:19,504
The new horror comes
stumbling towards them

472
00:23:19,506 --> 00:23:22,273
which is the zombie.

473
00:23:22,275 --> 00:23:24,475
He really reinvents the zombie

474
00:23:24,477 --> 00:23:27,645
and the zombie becomes one
of the great new monsters.

475
00:23:31,116 --> 00:23:34,719
The image of the zombie
in the cemetery

476
00:23:34,721 --> 00:23:38,923
is a key image that we
all felt was so iconic

477
00:23:38,925 --> 00:23:41,559
and we patterned our
zombies for the series

478
00:23:41,561 --> 00:23:44,228
"The Walking Dead"
after that zombie.

479
00:23:47,699 --> 00:23:51,035
We patterned both in terms
of its kind of gait,

480
00:23:54,740 --> 00:23:56,274
his speed.

481
00:24:02,648 --> 00:24:06,184
Not only is it creepy,
but it just seems

482
00:24:06,186 --> 00:24:09,520
like it's unrelenting
and it's not going to stop.

483
00:24:09,522 --> 00:24:10,788
Before "Night of
the Living Dead,"

484
00:24:10,790 --> 00:24:12,457
there were movies like
"I Walk with a Zombie,"

485
00:24:12,459 --> 00:24:15,026
they were this sort
of tribal character.

486
00:24:15,028 --> 00:24:16,594
Very different.

487
00:24:16,596 --> 00:24:21,332
Now, arguably, the zombie is
as important as the werewolf.

488
00:24:21,334 --> 00:24:23,334
But right below the vampire

489
00:24:23,336 --> 00:24:25,703
is probably the most
important horror monster

490
00:24:25,705 --> 00:24:27,939
in the history of scary movies.

491
00:24:27,941 --> 00:24:31,609
All these zombies
all go back to Romero.

492
00:24:31,611 --> 00:24:34,378
There's no movie director that's
responsible for the vampire.

493
00:24:34,380 --> 00:24:37,248
There's no movie director that's
responsible for Frankenstein.

494
00:24:37,250 --> 00:24:39,650
There's no movie director that's
responsible for the werewolf.

495
00:24:39,652 --> 00:24:41,986
There's people who've
made key movies of that.

496
00:24:41,988 --> 00:24:45,289
But, those are much
older characters,

497
00:24:45,291 --> 00:24:48,192
which have this kind
of literary pedigree.

498
00:24:48,194 --> 00:24:51,229
And while there have been
undead and zombies, et cetera,

499
00:24:51,231 --> 00:24:54,298
what we know of as a zombie,

500
00:24:54,300 --> 00:24:58,669
the kind of the it's alive
moment of it, was 1968,

501
00:24:58,671 --> 00:25:01,873
George Romero in "Night of
the Living Dead" in Pittsburgh.

502
00:25:02,474 --> 00:25:03,941
Dead face!

503
00:25:07,412 --> 00:25:08,713
Hold it.

504
00:25:08,715 --> 00:25:10,047
Don't smile.

505
00:25:10,049 --> 00:25:14,085
Smiling is your enemy.

506
00:25:14,087 --> 00:25:16,254
Follow the sound guys!

507
00:25:26,565 --> 00:25:30,167
What are George Romero's
rules of zombies?

508
00:25:30,169 --> 00:25:31,235
Aria.

509
00:25:31,237 --> 00:25:34,772
That zombies,
they, they walk slow.

510
00:25:34,774 --> 00:25:37,041
They drag their feet
when they're walking.

511
00:25:37,043 --> 00:25:37,975
Jared, what else?

512
00:25:37,977 --> 00:25:39,744
And they don't smile or laugh.

513
00:25:39,746 --> 00:25:41,412
They don't smile or laugh.

514
00:25:41,414 --> 00:25:43,614
When they're human,
the way they die

515
00:25:43,616 --> 00:25:45,917
is the way they're going
to stay when they're zombies

516
00:25:45,919 --> 00:25:47,652
until they turn into dust.

517
00:25:47,654 --> 00:25:49,120
What is the purpose
of a zombie?

518
00:25:49,122 --> 00:25:50,254
Aria.

519
00:25:50,256 --> 00:25:52,456
They like to eat people.

520
00:25:52,458 --> 00:25:54,158
They don't live
to do anything else.

521
00:25:54,160 --> 00:25:56,193
They just like to eat
and eat and eat.

522
00:25:56,195 --> 00:25:58,963
You guys remember what
I said, the need to feed?

523
00:25:58,965 --> 00:25:59,830
Remember?

524
00:25:59,832 --> 00:26:00,765
Say it again.

525
00:26:00,767 --> 00:26:01,832
The need to feed!

526
00:26:01,834 --> 00:26:02,767
Say it again.

527
00:26:02,769 --> 00:26:03,701
The need to feed!

528
00:26:03,703 --> 00:26:04,635
Again.

529
00:26:04,637 --> 00:26:05,703
The need to feed!

530
00:26:05,705 --> 00:26:07,371
That is it!

531
00:26:12,344 --> 00:26:14,845
To me there's something, um,

532
00:26:14,847 --> 00:26:17,882
definitive and classical
about the terror

533
00:26:17,884 --> 00:26:19,150
and the simplicity.

534
00:26:19,152 --> 00:26:21,686
It's not overblown.

535
00:26:21,688 --> 00:26:23,154
She gets in the car,
what do you do?

536
00:26:23,156 --> 00:26:24,455
You undo the clutch.

537
00:26:24,457 --> 00:26:26,791
She goes and she blows it
and runs into the tree!

538
00:26:26,793 --> 00:26:28,793
I mean, oh my God!

539
00:26:32,397 --> 00:26:35,499
Every shot does feel
iconic at this point.

540
00:26:35,501 --> 00:26:37,935
And I'm speaking of these
first 10 minutes.

541
00:26:37,937 --> 00:26:39,503
Every shot is iconic.

542
00:26:42,474 --> 00:26:44,675
It doesn't feel storyboarded.

543
00:26:44,677 --> 00:26:48,813
Everything feels organically,
like it's organically unfolding.

544
00:26:53,485 --> 00:26:55,753
She sees the lonely house
in the distance

545
00:26:55,755 --> 00:26:58,489
and that's sort
of another iconic shot.

546
00:27:01,793 --> 00:27:06,864
This to me is one of the great
sequences in any movie.

547
00:27:13,705 --> 00:27:17,074
Duane Jones,
a classically trained actor,

548
00:27:17,076 --> 00:27:19,577
played the role
of Ben, the hero.

549
00:27:19,579 --> 00:27:21,879
One of the things amazing
to me when I saw it this time,

550
00:27:21,881 --> 00:27:24,081
and it really blew my mind,

551
00:27:24,083 --> 00:27:27,118
was the fact that no one

552
00:27:27,120 --> 00:27:31,355
reacts to Duane Jones,
or the character

553
00:27:31,357 --> 00:27:34,025
as a black man.

554
00:27:34,027 --> 00:27:35,092
It's alright.

555
00:27:35,094 --> 00:27:36,861
There really wasn't
an audition.

556
00:27:36,863 --> 00:27:38,796
Uh, you know, we never
auditioned Duane.

557
00:27:38,798 --> 00:27:41,132
He was just a beautifully
impressive guy.

558
00:27:41,134 --> 00:27:44,135
He was a really
beautiful person, too.

559
00:27:44,137 --> 00:27:46,437
The script wasn't written,
the character wasn't described

560
00:27:46,439 --> 00:27:50,074
as white, black,
yellow, red, or anything.

561
00:27:50,076 --> 00:27:51,909
And we thought we were
doing the right thing

562
00:27:51,911 --> 00:27:56,514
by not changing the script
when we decided to use Duane.

563
00:27:56,516 --> 00:28:01,886
Here is a white woman,
very pale, blonde woman,

564
00:28:01,888 --> 00:28:04,689
who runs into a house

565
00:28:04,691 --> 00:28:09,393
and is rescued by a black man.

566
00:28:09,395 --> 00:28:10,995
And there's no reaction!

567
00:28:10,997 --> 00:28:13,564
There's a pump out here that's
locked, is there a key?

568
00:28:13,566 --> 00:28:15,066
She's out of it, she's scared,

569
00:28:15,068 --> 00:28:16,701
she's frightened,
but not of him.

570
00:28:16,703 --> 00:28:21,806
Which in 1968, as strange
as it seems, was still something

571
00:28:21,808 --> 00:28:24,909
that the average audience
really would have noticed.

572
00:28:24,911 --> 00:28:29,680
It would have registered to them
as something different.

573
00:28:29,682 --> 00:28:32,249
It felt like such a modern
movie in that obviously

574
00:28:32,251 --> 00:28:33,884
it was never remarked
upon that he was black.

575
00:28:33,886 --> 00:28:35,419
Nobody said anything about it

576
00:28:35,421 --> 00:28:36,754
the way they did
in other movies.

577
00:28:36,756 --> 00:28:39,190
And keep in mind,
this was a time

578
00:28:39,192 --> 00:28:41,559
when there was
a hugely popular TV show,

579
00:28:41,561 --> 00:28:43,527
"The Andy Griffith Show,"
taking place in the south,

580
00:28:43,529 --> 00:28:46,464
and there were
no black people in it.

581
00:28:46,466 --> 00:28:49,133
So that to have
this mainstream culture

582
00:28:49,135 --> 00:28:53,370
refuse to acknowledge
any kind of black catalyst

583
00:28:53,372 --> 00:28:56,340
and to have it there
and not be remarked upon,

584
00:28:56,342 --> 00:28:58,342
it really felt
like a brand new day.

585
00:28:58,344 --> 00:29:01,946
I don't think anyone had ever
seen anything like that,

586
00:29:01,948 --> 00:29:03,380
in the 60s.

587
00:29:03,382 --> 00:29:06,383
Chiz Schultz produced
television specials

588
00:29:06,385 --> 00:29:09,620
starring Harry Belafonte
in the late 1960s.

589
00:29:09,622 --> 00:29:11,489
We had Petula Clark

590
00:29:11,491 --> 00:29:14,325
who was the top
British singer at the time.

591
00:29:14,327 --> 00:29:16,560
And they had a number together.

592
00:29:16,562 --> 00:29:18,662
And at one point toward the end

593
00:29:18,664 --> 00:29:22,867
Harry links arms with Petula
and they sing the final verse.

594
00:29:22,869 --> 00:29:25,202
And we finished
dress rehearsal.

595
00:29:25,204 --> 00:29:30,174
And the man in charge of
advertising for Chrysler said,

596
00:29:30,176 --> 00:29:34,445
"Belafonte cannot
touch Petula Clark."

597
00:29:34,447 --> 00:29:37,548
And we were sort of in shock.

598
00:29:37,550 --> 00:29:40,417
And Belafonte said, "I'm not
sure I understood you."

599
00:29:40,419 --> 00:29:43,220
He said, "There will be
no touching of Miss Clark."

600
00:29:43,222 --> 00:29:46,791
Remember, we have to sell
cars in the South."

601
00:29:46,793 --> 00:29:49,293
And Harry said,
"Give me just a minute."

602
00:29:49,295 --> 00:29:52,396
And he called
the president of Chrysler.

603
00:29:52,398 --> 00:29:55,132
And he said, "You should know
I'm calling a press conference

604
00:29:55,134 --> 00:29:57,835
in 10 minutes
to say that Chrysler

605
00:29:57,837 --> 00:30:01,639
will not allow me
to touch Petula Clark."

606
00:30:01,641 --> 00:30:03,974
We went into air time.

607
00:30:03,976 --> 00:30:05,442
The taping.

608
00:30:05,444 --> 00:30:08,045
Harry and Petula linked arms.

609
00:30:08,047 --> 00:30:10,614
But that was not unusual.

610
00:30:10,616 --> 00:30:12,516
That was the atmosphere
at the time.

611
00:30:12,518 --> 00:30:16,320
We were only a year past
"Guess Who's Coming to Dinner"

612
00:30:16,322 --> 00:30:18,589
which had made its
entire subject

613
00:30:18,591 --> 00:30:21,125
the shockingness
of inter-racial marriage.

614
00:30:21,127 --> 00:30:24,361
Mom, this is John.

615
00:30:26,898 --> 00:30:31,035
Doc, Doc, Doctor Prentiss.

616
00:30:31,037 --> 00:30:34,638
I'm so pleased to meet you.

617
00:30:34,640 --> 00:30:36,874
I'm pleased to meet
you, Mrs. Drayton.

618
00:30:36,876 --> 00:30:40,044
"Guess Who's Coming to Dinner,"
was criticized for taking pains

619
00:30:40,046 --> 00:30:42,346
not to offend white moviegoers

620
00:30:42,348 --> 00:30:46,483
and for being out of touch
with the racial storms of 1967.

621
00:30:46,485 --> 00:30:48,219
And it never occurred
to me that I might fall

622
00:30:48,221 --> 00:30:49,620
in love with a Negro!

623
00:30:49,622 --> 00:30:52,389
Of Sidney Poitier's character,
H. Rap Brown said:

624
00:30:56,194 --> 00:30:59,563
This kind of criticism
wasn't new to Poitier.

625
00:30:59,565 --> 00:31:02,466
I remember watching
Sidney Poitier

626
00:31:02,468 --> 00:31:06,136
in the Stanley Kramer film,
"The Defiant Ones."

627
00:31:06,138 --> 00:31:08,405
And, uh, it was him
and Tony Curtis

628
00:31:08,407 --> 00:31:13,210
playing these two convicts
who escape from the chain gang,

629
00:31:13,212 --> 00:31:16,080
and near the very
end of the film,

630
00:31:16,082 --> 00:31:18,616
they're trying to get
to this rail road, right?

631
00:31:22,821 --> 00:31:25,222
But Tony can't
hold on, he can't,

632
00:31:25,224 --> 00:31:27,191
the train's moving too fast.

633
00:31:27,193 --> 00:31:29,593
So instead of Sidney
lets Tony drop,

634
00:31:29,595 --> 00:31:31,462
Sidney falls off, too.

635
00:31:31,464 --> 00:31:32,897
And then you see
the last scene,

636
00:31:32,899 --> 00:31:36,934
and Sidney's cradling
Tony Curtis in his arms,

637
00:31:36,936 --> 00:31:39,036
and he starts
singing this song.

638
00:31:39,038 --> 00:31:45,509
♪ If I ever do see his face once
more, he never get home again ♪

639
00:31:45,511 --> 00:31:48,279
Cradling Tony, you know,
as the law enforcement people

640
00:31:48,281 --> 00:31:49,780
come down on them.

641
00:31:49,782 --> 00:31:51,315
And I remember
thinking back then

642
00:31:51,317 --> 00:31:53,717
when I was 15, 16 years old,

643
00:31:53,719 --> 00:31:55,886
Sidney, you crazy, man?

644
00:31:55,888 --> 00:31:57,755
Let that white man go.

645
00:31:57,757 --> 00:32:00,324
Save yourself, you know.

646
00:32:00,326 --> 00:32:03,193
Because it was like,
he was always becoming, at,

647
00:32:03,195 --> 00:32:09,366
by that time, he was becoming
sort of like this, this savior.

648
00:32:09,368 --> 00:32:12,703
African American heroes
in the mid-60s in movies

649
00:32:12,705 --> 00:32:15,372
were allowed
to be really smart,

650
00:32:15,374 --> 00:32:17,975
they weren't necessary
allowed to be aggressive

651
00:32:17,977 --> 00:32:20,044
or strong or tough.

652
00:32:20,046 --> 00:32:22,413
I mean, Poitier started
to break that barrier

653
00:32:22,415 --> 00:32:25,015
in "In the Heat of the Night,"
but the most he could do

654
00:32:25,017 --> 00:32:27,985
was slap a white man
in the face

655
00:32:27,987 --> 00:32:31,388
after he is slapped in the face
by that white man.

656
00:32:34,526 --> 00:32:37,361
Poitier played a detective
who in this scene

657
00:32:37,363 --> 00:32:41,865
dared to interrogate
a rich white man.

658
00:32:41,867 --> 00:32:43,968
You saw it.

659
00:32:43,970 --> 00:32:45,302
I saw it.

660
00:32:45,304 --> 00:32:48,572
The slap was
an electric moment in 1967.

661
00:32:48,574 --> 00:32:52,509
Then all of a sudden
Duane Jones is like the lead,

662
00:32:52,511 --> 00:32:55,279
basically in
an all-white film.

663
00:32:57,782 --> 00:33:01,952
But he comes across as a very
strong, focused character.

664
00:33:01,954 --> 00:33:06,623
Duane was very upset whenever
he had to do anything violent.

665
00:33:06,625 --> 00:33:09,226
He's a, you know, very
sensitive kind of a guy.

666
00:33:09,228 --> 00:33:11,061
And what's a really
telling scene

667
00:33:11,063 --> 00:33:13,197
is when he slaps the women.

668
00:33:16,101 --> 00:33:18,369
It's even more intense
than when Sidney

669
00:33:18,371 --> 00:33:21,572
hits what's-his-name
in "In the Heat of the Night."

670
00:33:21,574 --> 00:33:22,940
He really slapped her.

671
00:33:22,942 --> 00:33:26,210
Particularly, "I'm going
to slap a white woman"

672
00:33:26,212 --> 00:33:28,412
and shoot a white guy.

673
00:33:28,414 --> 00:33:31,749
"And uh, I'm going
to be in trouble!"

674
00:33:31,751 --> 00:33:34,218
And then when
he shoots the guy!

675
00:33:34,220 --> 00:33:36,286
You know, he shoots the guy!

676
00:33:36,288 --> 00:33:39,323
I said, "This is a bold
black man for 1967!"

677
00:33:39,325 --> 00:33:40,557
Very bold.

678
00:33:40,559 --> 00:33:42,693
You would never put
"Night of the Living Dead"

679
00:33:42,695 --> 00:33:45,295
on the spectrum
of blaxploitation

680
00:33:45,297 --> 00:33:47,531
and black power movies
that started to happen

681
00:33:47,533 --> 00:33:49,299
in the late 60s and early 70s,

682
00:33:49,301 --> 00:33:52,036
but in a way,
you know, it really,

683
00:33:52,038 --> 00:33:54,571
it precedes "Shaft,"
it precedes "Superfly,"

684
00:33:54,573 --> 00:33:56,206
it precedes all those movies

685
00:33:56,208 --> 00:33:58,976
where the African American
main character

686
00:33:58,978 --> 00:34:01,245
was suddenly
no longer accommodationist

687
00:34:01,247 --> 00:34:03,047
and exceptional and polite.

688
00:34:03,049 --> 00:34:05,149
He's black.

689
00:34:05,151 --> 00:34:07,051
He's brutal.

690
00:34:07,053 --> 00:34:08,419
He's boss.

691
00:34:08,421 --> 00:34:12,723
But, you know,
tough and empowered.

692
00:34:12,725 --> 00:34:15,526
And of course we discussed it,
and Duane, as I said,

693
00:34:15,528 --> 00:34:19,563
was the most sensitive
among us to the racial issue

694
00:34:19,565 --> 00:34:23,734
and how some of that
stuff might resonate.

695
00:34:23,736 --> 00:34:25,702
We said, "Well, wait,
it was in the script

696
00:34:25,704 --> 00:34:27,738
before the guy
was black."

697
00:34:27,740 --> 00:34:31,642
And, but he was saying, "Well
yeah, but he is black now!"

698
00:34:31,644 --> 00:34:33,677
And so you have
to think about that.

699
00:34:33,679 --> 00:34:35,813
And as I said,
I've in recent years

700
00:34:35,815 --> 00:34:38,148
come to the thought that maybe
we should have explored

701
00:34:38,150 --> 00:34:39,951
the racial issue a little bit.

702
00:34:39,952 --> 00:34:44,488
We thought we were being really
hip by not changing the script.

703
00:34:44,490 --> 00:34:46,523
I think it's also
what made the movie

704
00:34:46,525 --> 00:34:49,126
feel like it belonged
to another generation.

705
00:34:49,128 --> 00:34:51,829
That sense of not
wringing its hands

706
00:34:51,831 --> 00:34:54,631
and having to talk,
stop for a moment,

707
00:34:54,633 --> 00:34:57,734
they're all being pilloried
by zombies and saying,

708
00:34:57,736 --> 00:35:00,370
"You know, Ben,
when I was a boy,

709
00:35:00,372 --> 00:35:02,673
we had a colored maid
and she never worked

710
00:35:02,675 --> 00:35:03,841
as hard as you
did for us."

711
00:35:03,843 --> 00:35:06,543
I mean, by not having
a scene like that,

712
00:35:06,545 --> 00:35:10,180
it felt exciting and new.

713
00:35:10,182 --> 00:35:12,382
It truly did.

714
00:35:12,384 --> 00:35:13,917
Hold it!
Don't shoot!

715
00:35:13,919 --> 00:35:14,985
We're from town.

716
00:35:14,987 --> 00:35:16,587
A radio!

717
00:35:16,589 --> 00:35:18,555
One great thing about
"Night of the Living Dead"

718
00:35:18,557 --> 00:35:21,725
is that it doesn't resort
to the cliché of like,

719
00:35:21,727 --> 00:35:24,528
well, everybody would put
aside their differences

720
00:35:24,530 --> 00:35:26,730
in the face of such
a big threat.

721
00:35:26,732 --> 00:35:28,098
How long you guys
been down there?

722
00:35:28,100 --> 00:35:29,600
I could've used
some help up here.

723
00:35:29,602 --> 00:35:31,001
That's the cellar.
It's the safest place.

724
00:35:31,003 --> 00:35:33,537
Which is this hokey thing
that horror movies

725
00:35:33,539 --> 00:35:35,606
and sci fi movies still do.

726
00:35:35,608 --> 00:35:40,577
That no matter, you know,
how much you may differ

727
00:35:40,579 --> 00:35:43,514
in real life, all that's
going to get cast aside

728
00:35:43,516 --> 00:35:44,681
because you have
to fight the monster

729
00:35:44,683 --> 00:35:46,049
or fight the alien or whatever.

730
00:35:46,051 --> 00:35:47,284
The cellar.

731
00:35:47,286 --> 00:35:49,019
The cellar, there's
only one door, right?

732
00:35:49,021 --> 00:35:51,788
Just one door, that's
all we have to protect.

733
00:35:51,790 --> 00:35:54,958
Tom and I fixed it so it locks
and boards from the inside.

734
00:35:54,960 --> 00:35:56,660
But up here, all these windows?

735
00:35:56,662 --> 00:35:58,996
Why, we'd never know where
they were going to hit us next!

736
00:35:58,998 --> 00:36:00,864
You got a point,
Mr. Cooper.

737
00:36:00,866 --> 00:36:03,000
But down in the cellar,
there's no place to run to.

738
00:36:03,002 --> 00:36:04,835
Romero actually suggests that,

739
00:36:04,837 --> 00:36:07,070
nope, it's going to be embedded

740
00:36:07,072 --> 00:36:09,406
even in the way
you choose to fight,

741
00:36:09,408 --> 00:36:11,708
even in where
you choose to hide.

742
00:36:11,710 --> 00:36:13,977
But the cellar is
the strongest place.

743
00:36:13,979 --> 00:36:15,712
The cellar is a death trap.

