987
00:47:16,908 --> 00:47:21,678
that the people who seem
most likely to be able

988
00:47:21,680 --> 00:47:24,981
to thwart this incursion
of the living dead

989
00:47:24,983 --> 00:47:27,617
look like a lynch mob.

990
00:47:27,619 --> 00:47:29,786
The resonance for people
who would have spent

991
00:47:29,788 --> 00:47:31,321
the last 10 years

992
00:47:31,323 --> 00:47:37,093
watching white southerners
vow to prevent

993
00:47:37,095 --> 00:47:41,297
the desegregation of schools,
for instance, um,

994
00:47:41,299 --> 00:47:44,934
it would've been
really pretty clear.

995
00:47:44,936 --> 00:47:47,370
And dogs in "Night
of the Living Dead,"

996
00:47:47,372 --> 00:47:49,672
there's a very specific
cultural resonance.

997
00:47:49,674 --> 00:47:52,675
You know, black men
being chased by dogs

998
00:47:52,677 --> 00:47:57,647
is one of the ugliest images
of the civil rights movement,

999
00:47:57,649 --> 00:48:02,619
and was very much part of
the national visual vocabulary

1000
00:48:02,621 --> 00:48:05,588
of any moviegoer,
other than a very little kid,

1001
00:48:05,590 --> 00:48:07,724
who would have gone
to see this movie.

1002
00:48:07,726 --> 00:48:12,228
And again, it connects
to this, this idea that

1003
00:48:12,230 --> 00:48:17,166
it's not as simple as
the good guys vs. the undead.

1004
00:48:17,168 --> 00:48:22,305
There are the good guys,
the not good guys,

1005
00:48:22,307 --> 00:48:24,774
and the living dead.

1006
00:48:24,776 --> 00:48:26,910
They seem to be getting
a certain amount of pleasure

1007
00:48:26,912 --> 00:48:30,246
out of putting down these
monsters and being able

1008
00:48:30,248 --> 00:48:35,184
to go out and hunt people
and lynch people.

1009
00:48:35,186 --> 00:48:37,353
They seem really real to me.

1010
00:48:37,355 --> 00:48:39,188
They felt real, those guys.

1011
00:48:39,190 --> 00:48:41,457
I wasn't sure they were actors.

1012
00:48:43,360 --> 00:48:47,764
It's a really interesting,
squirmy political aspect

1013
00:48:47,766 --> 00:48:50,366
of the movie that's
intentionally unsettling.

1014
00:48:50,368 --> 00:48:54,337
I think Romero wants you to feel
uncomfortable with the fact

1015
00:48:54,339 --> 00:48:57,941
that the so called victors
at the end of the movie

1016
00:48:57,943 --> 00:49:02,445
are exactly the kind of people
you're inclined not to root for.

1017
00:49:02,447 --> 00:49:05,448
You! Drag that on out of here
and throw it on the fire.

1018
00:49:05,450 --> 00:49:06,649
Nothing down here.

1019
00:49:06,651 --> 00:49:08,751
Alright, go ahead
and give him a hand.

1020
00:49:08,753 --> 00:49:09,919
Let's go check out the house.

1021
00:49:09,921 --> 00:49:12,388
There's something there.
I heard a noise.

1022
00:49:16,894 --> 00:49:18,061
Alright Vince,
hit him in the head.

1023
00:49:18,063 --> 00:49:20,063
Right between the eyes.

1024
00:49:23,000 --> 00:49:23,833
Good shot.

1025
00:49:23,835 --> 00:49:26,869
That was the ironic ending.

1026
00:49:26,871 --> 00:49:29,539
He refuses to go downstairs,
finally he survives

1027
00:49:29,541 --> 00:49:30,773
by going downstairs,

1028
00:49:30,775 --> 00:49:34,344
then when he comes back up
he gets gunned down.

1029
00:49:34,346 --> 00:49:37,347
'Cause he's mistaken
for one of the living dead.

1030
00:49:37,349 --> 00:49:38,348
Okay, he's dead.

1031
00:49:38,350 --> 00:49:39,449
Let's go get him.

1032
00:49:39,451 --> 00:49:41,250
That's another one
for the fire.

1033
00:49:41,252 --> 00:49:45,154
So, yeah, that ending was there
before we ever cast Duane.

1034
00:49:45,156 --> 00:49:49,292
And that was
the only time for me,

1035
00:49:49,294 --> 00:49:51,728
I, I put a racial thing to it.

1036
00:49:51,730 --> 00:49:55,565
You know, like, they saw him,
he didn't yell out,

1037
00:49:55,567 --> 00:49:57,767
he was a black man,
and they shot him.

1038
00:49:57,769 --> 00:50:01,637
My favorite scene was when,

1039
00:50:01,639 --> 00:50:06,376
probably when
the African man got shot,

1040
00:50:06,378 --> 00:50:08,244
when he wasn't even a zombie.

1041
00:50:08,246 --> 00:50:12,448
I thought they should know
if he's a zombie or not,

1042
00:50:12,450 --> 00:50:16,853
because if they knew he was
a zombie, they would have,

1043
00:50:16,855 --> 00:50:18,988
the zombie would have
attacked them already

1044
00:50:18,990 --> 00:50:20,323
and walked toward them.

1045
00:50:20,325 --> 00:50:25,294
But all he did was stand
up and they just shot him.

1046
00:50:28,999 --> 00:50:32,402
A lot of people talked
about that as a lynching

1047
00:50:32,404 --> 00:50:35,438
and saw a political
thread in it.

1048
00:50:35,440 --> 00:50:39,609
I think it's more of a shock
in terms of the way it violates

1049
00:50:39,611 --> 00:50:44,347
your sense of narrative
expectation than,

1050
00:50:44,349 --> 00:50:46,082
uh, politically.

1051
00:50:46,084 --> 00:50:50,019
When our protagonist does get
shot, utterly arbitrarily,

1052
00:50:50,021 --> 00:50:53,122
I think that's way
beyond a racist issue,

1053
00:50:53,124 --> 00:50:56,159
that's Romero just
speaking from the times

1054
00:50:56,161 --> 00:50:59,028
about a bleakness that
the culture was suffering.

1055
00:50:59,030 --> 00:51:01,264
If he had survived,
it would have been dishonest.

1056
00:51:01,266 --> 00:51:04,934
I mean, even as a kid
and I was, you know,

1057
00:51:04,936 --> 00:51:06,202
propping my eyes open
with toothpicks

1058
00:51:06,204 --> 00:51:09,105
trying to sleep a couple
of nights after.

1059
00:51:09,107 --> 00:51:13,576
It felt like that was the most
honest thing to do.

1060
00:51:13,578 --> 00:51:16,446
You know, it's a tradition
in films that you can escape.

1061
00:51:16,448 --> 00:51:17,980
There's always the idea
you can escape.

1062
00:51:17,982 --> 00:51:22,985
You might leave your past if
you were involved with the mob,

1063
00:51:22,987 --> 00:51:25,688
you would leave and you'd
have a new beginning.

1064
00:51:25,690 --> 00:51:28,157
It's a tradition all
the way back to Homer!

1065
00:51:28,159 --> 00:51:29,725
The new beginning.

1066
00:51:29,727 --> 00:51:31,694
You go home
and you start again.

1067
00:51:31,696 --> 00:51:33,930
You refresh
and you start again.

1068
00:51:33,932 --> 00:51:35,698
But, of course,
the apocalyptic filmmakers

1069
00:51:35,700 --> 00:51:37,066
take that away from you.

1070
00:51:37,068 --> 00:51:37,900
No.

1071
00:51:37,902 --> 00:51:39,168
Tomorrow may not come

1072
00:51:39,170 --> 00:51:40,436
the way you're planning on it.

1073
00:51:40,438 --> 00:51:41,971
You may not have
another chance.

1074
00:51:41,973 --> 00:51:44,073
The only reason to do
the fantasy film

1075
00:51:44,075 --> 00:51:47,610
or the horror film
is to sort of upset the order,

1076
00:51:47,612 --> 00:51:49,812
upset the balance of things.

1077
00:51:49,814 --> 00:51:53,216
And it seems to me, seemed to me
that the formula was always

1078
00:51:53,218 --> 00:51:54,817
to restore order, you know?

1079
00:51:54,819 --> 00:52:00,056
Put it back the way it was,
which seems, you know,

1080
00:52:00,058 --> 00:52:03,826
counterproductive to what
you're doing initially.

1081
00:52:03,828 --> 00:52:06,929
And, which is why it
made sense to me to have,

1082
00:52:06,931 --> 00:52:09,265
you know, "Night
of the Living Dead"

1083
00:52:09,267 --> 00:52:12,135
have this sort of tragic
and ironic ending.

1084
00:52:15,572 --> 00:52:19,809
The credits roll seconds
after Ben's death.

1085
00:52:19,811 --> 00:52:24,080
It's shockingly blasé
and detached.

1086
00:52:24,082 --> 00:52:26,682
It's as businesslike
as anything else in the film.

1087
00:52:26,684 --> 00:52:31,320
It may be the most emotionless
horror film of all time.

1088
00:52:33,390 --> 00:52:35,124
If it had been Sidney Poitier
in the movie,

1089
00:52:35,126 --> 00:52:37,426
he would have done that thing
and wave to everybody,

1090
00:52:37,428 --> 00:52:38,594
thrown his trench coat
over his shoulder,

1091
00:52:38,596 --> 00:52:40,263
and walked off
into the distance

1092
00:52:40,265 --> 00:52:43,065
as the haunting love theme
by Loulou piped into theaters

1093
00:52:43,067 --> 00:52:45,701
reminding us of the feat
he accomplished.

1094
00:52:45,703 --> 00:52:50,973
Um, and you know, that's,
it just felt so right.

1095
00:52:50,975 --> 00:52:52,542
It was the thing that was
probably more exciting

1096
00:52:52,544 --> 00:52:54,443
to everybody, when I
finally called the people

1097
00:52:54,445 --> 00:52:56,078
who did see it,
"Wasn't it great

1098
00:52:56,080 --> 00:52:58,514
that he does everything
and then gets shot?

1099
00:52:58,516 --> 00:53:00,816
Not only gets shot,
but right in the head!

1100
00:53:00,818 --> 00:53:03,619
So it's not like
you miss it."

1101
00:53:03,621 --> 00:53:09,559
It's completely terrifying
and the perfect ending.

1102
00:53:09,561 --> 00:53:12,094
Randy, light these
torches over here.

1103
00:53:17,334 --> 00:53:20,336
You really offered no comforts
to the audience at all.

1104
00:53:22,839 --> 00:53:26,809
No. But there's always
the refreshment stand!

1105
00:53:30,814 --> 00:53:33,382
Principal photography for
"Night of the Living Dead"

1106
00:53:33,384 --> 00:53:37,086
wrapped in November of 1967.

1107
00:53:37,088 --> 00:53:40,756
As Romero edited, the search
for investors continued.

1108
00:53:40,758 --> 00:53:42,692
And at first people
had no faith that we could

1109
00:53:42,694 --> 00:53:44,460
actually make a movie.

1110
00:53:44,462 --> 00:53:45,828
And it was only
when we were able

1111
00:53:45,830 --> 00:53:50,600
to actually show some dailies
and people saw that lips

1112
00:53:50,602 --> 00:53:55,471
were in sync
with the sound, um,

1113
00:53:55,473 --> 00:53:57,807
and they were able to say,
"It looks like a movie!"

1114
00:53:57,809 --> 00:54:00,343
And we'd say, "That's what
we're trying to tell ya!

1115
00:54:00,345 --> 00:54:03,379
One of these days it's gonna
grow up to be a movie!"

1116
00:54:03,381 --> 00:54:08,451
And, uh, you know,
so money dribbled in,

1117
00:54:08,453 --> 00:54:10,152
over the course
of several months.

1118
00:54:10,154 --> 00:54:11,754
And we were never certain
that we were ever

1119
00:54:11,756 --> 00:54:14,056
going to get enough
to finish it.

1120
00:54:14,058 --> 00:54:16,392
We didn't have money
for the sound mix.

1121
00:54:16,394 --> 00:54:18,327
So Russ Streiner
challenged the guy

1122
00:54:18,329 --> 00:54:20,997
who owns the lab
to a chess match,

1123
00:54:20,999 --> 00:54:23,032
and at stake was the sound mix.

1124
00:54:23,034 --> 00:54:24,900
And Russ beat the guy!

1125
00:54:24,902 --> 00:54:27,370
And won the sound mix!

1126
00:54:27,372 --> 00:54:30,973
So this was the kind of shit
that we were going through, man.

1127
00:54:44,154 --> 00:54:48,624
In January, 1968,
Vietnamese Revolutionary Forces

1128
00:54:48,626 --> 00:54:52,261
mounted a coordinated attack
on over 100 South Vietnamese

1129
00:54:52,263 --> 00:54:56,966
cities and towns, including
the U.S. Embassy in Saigon.

1130
00:54:59,736 --> 00:55:02,571
It was called the Tet Offensive
and it brought

1131
00:55:02,573 --> 00:55:04,674
some of the most disturbing
images to date

1132
00:55:04,676 --> 00:55:07,743
to prime time television.

1133
00:55:07,745 --> 00:55:09,979
For many, the war
seemed more dangerous

1134
00:55:09,981 --> 00:55:12,214
and pointless than ever.

1135
00:55:12,216 --> 00:55:16,085
Still, it would
continue until 1975.

1136
00:55:19,389 --> 00:55:22,658
President Lyndon B. Johnson
seemed better at facing facts

1137
00:55:22,660 --> 00:55:25,227
when it came
to domestic policy.

1138
00:55:25,229 --> 00:55:27,663
He commissioned a study
to investigate the causes

1139
00:55:27,665 --> 00:55:30,266
of the nation's race riots.

1140
00:55:30,268 --> 00:55:33,736
An unflinching wake-up call,
the Kerner Commission Report

1141
00:55:33,738 --> 00:55:35,237
warned that,

1142
00:55:42,145 --> 00:55:44,180
Regarding the ghetto,
it stated:

1143
00:55:51,121 --> 00:55:53,789
And while "black militancy"
may have added fuel

1144
00:55:53,791 --> 00:55:56,659
to the riots,
the primary cause was:

1145
00:55:58,528 --> 00:56:02,231
We are moving toward two
societies, separate and unequal

1146
00:56:02,233 --> 00:56:05,401
and if something isn't
done to stop this

1147
00:56:05,403 --> 00:56:08,938
in a very determined manner
things can really get worse.

1148
00:56:10,774 --> 00:56:12,875
A few days later
"Night of the Living Dead"

1149
00:56:12,877 --> 00:56:15,111
was finally completed.

1150
00:56:15,113 --> 00:56:18,681
Image 10 still needed
a distributor for the film.

1151
00:56:18,683 --> 00:56:21,217
With the hope of finding
one in New York City,

1152
00:56:21,219 --> 00:56:22,585
Romero and Streiner

1153
00:56:22,587 --> 00:56:25,287
pick up the first finished
print from the lab.

1154
00:56:25,289 --> 00:56:26,689
Threw it in the trunk
of the car.

1155
00:56:26,691 --> 00:56:31,093
Finished answer print,
drove it to New York

1156
00:56:31,095 --> 00:56:33,295
to see if anybody
wanted to show it.

1157
00:56:33,297 --> 00:56:36,766
And Russ and I are
driving to New York

1158
00:56:36,768 --> 00:56:38,033
and we hear on the radio

1159
00:56:38,035 --> 00:56:41,036
that Martin Luther King
had been assassinated.

1160
00:56:43,373 --> 00:56:45,908
And you know, of course we
have this sort of angry film

1161
00:56:45,910 --> 00:56:48,878
that, you know, has
this 60s stuff in it,

1162
00:56:48,880 --> 00:56:53,916
we had a black lead,
Duane, and, you know...

1163
00:56:55,786 --> 00:56:58,454
Several distributors
considered the film.

1164
00:56:58,456 --> 00:57:00,990
It did not ignite
a bidding war.

1165
00:57:00,992 --> 00:57:05,060
I think Romero was working
against all kinds of prejudices

1166
00:57:05,062 --> 00:57:07,696
against what he
was trying to do.

1167
00:57:07,698 --> 00:57:11,400
A, if you've never made a film,
you can't make a film.

1168
00:57:11,402 --> 00:57:13,169
You've got to have a whole
succession of films

1169
00:57:13,171 --> 00:57:15,271
in order to make a film.

1170
00:57:15,273 --> 00:57:19,008
Uh, I think he was working
against the fact of you have

1171
00:57:19,010 --> 00:57:23,479
to have millions of dollars
to make a feature film.

1172
00:57:23,481 --> 00:57:24,447
Well, you don't.

1173
00:57:24,449 --> 00:57:27,883
The movie only cost $114,000.

1174
00:57:27,885 --> 00:57:30,953
Um, that's a very,
very low budget now.

1175
00:57:30,955 --> 00:57:33,656
It was also a very,
very low budget then.

1176
00:57:33,658 --> 00:57:37,059
I think in '67,
the average studio movie

1177
00:57:37,061 --> 00:57:40,729
probably cost about three
or 3.5 million dollars.

1178
00:57:40,731 --> 00:57:43,833
So $114,000 is nothing.

1179
00:57:43,835 --> 00:57:45,968
The movie's in black
and white at a moment

1180
00:57:45,970 --> 00:57:49,205
when just about
everything in movies

1181
00:57:49,207 --> 00:57:50,840
had switched over to color.

1182
00:57:50,842 --> 00:57:54,443
A black and white movie
in 1968 was less playable.

1183
00:57:54,445 --> 00:57:56,712
Theaters were less
interested in booking it.

1184
00:57:56,714 --> 00:58:01,050
Um, of course he was working
with a cast of unknowns.

1185
00:58:01,052 --> 00:58:04,753
That adds up to a very tough
set of circumstances,

1186
00:58:04,755 --> 00:58:09,058
especially when you're
effectively rebooting a genre

1187
00:58:09,060 --> 00:58:13,229
that hasn't done much
for the last several years.

1188
00:58:13,231 --> 00:58:15,064
Columbia, I think, was
the first place we went to

1189
00:58:15,066 --> 00:58:16,665
and they actually held
it for a little while

1190
00:58:16,667 --> 00:58:19,268
and it looked as if they were
really seriously thinking

1191
00:58:19,270 --> 00:58:20,769
about releasing it.

1192
00:58:20,771 --> 00:58:23,105
Columbia turned it down.

1193
00:58:23,107 --> 00:58:26,909
American International Pictures,
known for low budget biker,

1194
00:58:26,911 --> 00:58:31,680
psychedelic, and Roger Corman's
Edgar Allan Poe movies,

1195
00:58:31,682 --> 00:58:34,583
said they'd release it,
but under one condition.

1196
00:58:34,585 --> 00:58:37,319
They wanted to change
the ending and they said,

1197
00:58:37,321 --> 00:58:42,191
"It's just too dark,"
and, you know, so,

1198
00:58:42,193 --> 00:58:44,827
we boldly said, "Fuggetaboutit!

1199
00:58:44,829 --> 00:58:47,496
This is our movie!"

1200
00:58:47,498 --> 00:58:50,432
And we walked, and we never
got the time of day

1201
00:58:50,434 --> 00:58:52,601
from anybody else for a while.

1202
00:58:52,603 --> 00:58:58,173
And we finally hired, someone
recommended a sales agent,

1203
00:58:58,175 --> 00:59:01,577
um, you know, somebody
who's business it is

1204
00:59:01,579 --> 00:59:05,381
to go and, you know,
try to find distribution.

1205
00:59:05,383 --> 00:59:07,950
And so we hired this
guy and he took it,

1206
00:59:07,952 --> 00:59:11,053
and eventually got
a deal with Walter Reade.

1207
00:59:11,055 --> 00:59:13,556
"Night of the Living Dead"
was first released in theaters

1208
00:59:13,558 --> 00:59:17,660
and drive-ins
on October 2nd, 1968.

1209
00:59:20,297 --> 00:59:21,764
When we first saw
"Night of the Living Dead"

1210
00:59:21,766 --> 00:59:23,632
we went to a drive in
to watch it.

1211
00:59:23,634 --> 00:59:25,701
It was the first time we said,

1212
00:59:25,703 --> 00:59:28,237
"It really is a movie,
isn't it?"

1213
00:59:28,239 --> 00:59:29,738
'Cause we were able
to go to the drive in

1214
00:59:29,740 --> 00:59:34,043
and buy some dogs and some
popcorn, check out

1215
00:59:34,045 --> 00:59:35,377
"Night of the Living Dead."

1216
00:59:35,379 --> 00:59:37,580
"Night of the Living Dead"
in New York was treated

1217
00:59:37,582 --> 00:59:39,615
as a grindhouse movie,

1218
00:59:39,617 --> 00:59:41,116
and it was booked
as a grindhouse movie.

1219
00:59:41,118 --> 00:59:43,686
It played on the New Amsterdam
theater on 42nd Street,

1220
00:59:43,688 --> 00:59:49,792
which was like a 7th run,
a bad theater.

1221
00:59:49,794 --> 00:59:52,294
New York's 42nd Street
was the epicenter

1222
00:59:52,296 --> 00:59:55,664
of the grindhouse circuit.

1223
00:59:55,666 --> 00:59:59,001
These are all exploitation films
that have no artistic ambition.

1224
00:59:59,003 --> 01:00:02,004
